snippet.textDisplay:
Too long: Supernatural.
There are a few episodes in the later seasons where the show kind of acknowledges its fanbase or other things that make for decent episodes but it's mostly not worth the watch past the original 5 seasons.

Too short: Tuca & Bertie.
This one is super disappointing because it had a great pace and an amazing balance between serious and goofy elements and it set up a following season in a very natural way. Netflix didn't know if it would be popular enough to renew it for that following season and the show and decided to end it there though. Definitely worth watching in its current state, though, and it is in the same style as BoJack Horseman but a different universe and a more cartoonish world.

Just right: BoJack Horseman.
I haven't completely finished BoJack Horseman yet but it is a brilliant show overall that knew where it was going and was never planning on dragging it out. Although the ending it currently has is not what the writers intended but rather a result of Netflix cutting it off for budgeting purposes, the writers did an excellent job of giving it a proper ending that has been set up throughout the show's entire running time. I cannot stress how much respect I have for this show. Like Tuca & Bertie, it has a great balance of goofy light side stories and heavier topics. It handles mental illness, addiction, abuse, child stars, and many issues that arise in the film and television industries in an easy to understand way. The characters are built to be likable, not as in they have friendly personalities but in a way that viewers are given characters that they like that they can hate as well as characters that they can relate to, admire, or see in the real world. I could write an in-depth essay for each character, analyzing how they've developed and how well-shaped they are. While some episode conflicts are solved with a ridiculous plan that wraps everything up in a neat bow, e.g. Mr. Peanutbutter spent millions of dollars on pasta strainers to wear like hats and had to use them to save an underwater city from a giant spaghetti spill that was being cooked in the ocean, the more serious plots don't end perfectly and have realistic twists and turns that make the viewer wonder if it'll come back later to bite the characters back. I highly recommend this show to everyone, it is a gem in today's television market.
snippet.textOriginal:
Too long: Supernatural.
There are a few episodes in the later seasons where the show kind of acknowledges its fanbase or other things that make for decent episodes but it's mostly not worth the watch past the original 5 seasons.

Too short: Tuca & Bertie.
This one is super disappointing because it had a great pace and an amazing balance between serious and goofy elements and it set up a following season in a very natural way. Netflix didn't know if it would be popular enough to renew it for that following season and the show and decided to end it there though. Definitely worth watching in its current state, though, and it is in the same style as BoJack Horseman but a different universe and a more cartoonish world.

Just right: BoJack Horseman.
I haven't completely finished BoJack Horseman yet but it is a brilliant show overall that knew where it was going and was never planning on dragging it out. Although the ending it currently has is not what the writers intended but rather a result of Netflix cutting it off for budgeting purposes, the writers did an excellent job of giving it a proper ending that has been set up throughout the show's entire running time. I cannot stress how much respect I have for this show. Like Tuca & Bertie, it has a great balance of goofy light side stories and heavier topics. It handles mental illness, addiction, abuse, child stars, and many issues that arise in the film and television industries in an easy to understand way. The characters are built to be likable, not as in they have friendly personalities but in a way that viewers are given characters that they like that they can hate as well as characters that they can relate to, admire, or see in the real world. I could write an in-depth essay for each character, analyzing how they've developed and how well-shaped they are. While some episode conflicts are solved with a ridiculous plan that wraps everything up in a neat bow, e.g. Mr. Peanutbutter spent millions of dollars on pasta strainers to wear like hats and had to use them to save an underwater city from a giant spaghetti spill that was being cooked in the ocean, the more serious plots don't end perfectly and have realistic twists and turns that make the viewer wonder if it'll come back later to bite the characters back. I highly recommend this show to everyone, it is a gem in today's television market.

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like Star Wars is a great example of this.

As much as I would love to continue the Star Wars franchise for forever, I feel like it should have ended with the ending George Lucas intended for in the Empire Strikes back. Bringing up a new imbalance to the Star Wars galaxy and Rey becoming the overall hero and "chosen one" completely disregarded anything Lucas wrote for the prequels and original trilogy (in that Anakin Skywalker was to bring balance). Lucas said himself that all of his movies were built around Anakin's journey to fulfilling the prophesy as the chosen one and the Disney sequels basically threw that idea out completely in order to make their new hero mean something

lmao sorry that was long but I think the sequels serve to be an excellent example of extended plot lines tainting the magic of the originals

Legend of Korra seasons 1 and 2 definitely had a lot of problems, many of which made me frustrated with how they shaped Avatar's characters (Aang being a lousy father infuriates me)
But the later seasons, which they didn't expect to get, were actually amazing and took the show in places that even Avatar didn't go.
I would argue the Legend of Korra had the inverse of the problem you're describing. They thought they were only getting one season so they rushed a story and it didn't quite work. TLDR: Seasons 3 and 4 of LoK are really good, despite seasons 1 and 2
